<br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fas.org/nuke/hew/Usa/Tests/Rwmohawk2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Reasons to go nuclear!</span><hr size=1> MONEY!<br><br>Asteroids are goldmines. When this solar system formed a long time ago the early planets and other assorted rocks were hot balls of liquid. Earth is the largest terrestrial(rocky ok) body. Then in decreasing order of size you have Venus, Mars, all the various moons and there are plenty of those (atleast 22 around Saturn alone), the asteroids which might measure hundreds of kilometres across and so on all the way down to dust.<br>The larger ones had a degree of gravity and because of this the heavier elements in the mix sank to the cores. There was still a trace near the surface. The interiors of planets are violent upheaving churning chaos and some heavier stuff was trapped in the crust when it hardened. Things like Gold, Platinum and Uranium etc are very rare because of this and therefore very expensive.<br><br>Not so in Asteroids.<br><br>Mars may be a rich potential mining source as it is smaller than Earth so less goodies might have sunk. Like all of space it is certainly untouched to date and that fact alone makes it a good place to prospect. Even if it is only identical to Earths makeup. Having some gravity (one third that of Earth) would be both helpful to humans and add to the cost of transportation.<br>On the other hand there are Asteroids. Easier to reach and with virtually no gravity to speak of. The various elements would be equally distributed and easily accessible in a very pure form. The most detailed study of an asteroid shows that it contains precious metals worth at least $20 trillion. <br><br>Best of all is these resources would be incredibly easy to mine and require almost no refinement or processing. Some foil to make a solar oven, grinders to break up the rock(optional) and magnets to separate out the metals are all you really need. Not that you are limited to Gold and other precious metals. Everything is out there. Even volatiles. That means you can extract oxygen and water for the crew and even rocket fuel for any chemical engines brought along(perhaps some shuttlecraft for ferrying between the main ship and target asteroid).<br><br>With nuclear rockets we could start colonising space with style.<br><br>Gold rush in space.<br><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/sci/tech/newsid_401000/401227.stm">news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/sci/tech/newsid_401000/401227.stm</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br><br>Asteroid mining. Scientific American.<br><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.sciam.com/askexpert/astronomy/astronomy3.html">www.sciam.com/askexpert/astronomy/astronomy3.html</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br><br>PERMANENT.<br><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.permanent.com/index.htm">www.permanent.com/index.htm</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br><br>Asteroid News From Explorezone.Com.<br><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://explorezone.com/news/asteroids.htm">explorezone.com/news/asteroids.htm</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br> <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>Nuclear power is the next logical step for serious space travel. The technology required to colonise the solar system exists now!<a href="http://www.nuclearspace.net/">NUCLEARSPACE.NET</a><img src="http://a676.g.akamai.net/f/676/987/12h/photos.netclubs.com/live/photos/Clubs/t/p/tpeidaeb7nah3e2e0188nkppm4/OrionNow2.gif" border="0"></a> </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 15<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/12/02 1:58:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Going nuclear</span><hr size=1> I believe, as always, that one of the &quot;have-not&quot; nations would have the most to gain from going nuclear in space. The big economic powers, the USA, Japan, and Europe, have a hammerlock on global resources through their intricate systems of global corporations. They have no incentive to open a new arena of competition where they would have to start from scratch, on a more even basis with everyone else, and with no special or long-established advantages. Those with the greatest vested interest are least likely to support innovation. In the early 20th century, the British Navy was completely dominant on the world's oceans. It was reluctant to adopt the new technology of the submarine even though its early sub technology was better than that of its arch rival, Germany. To the British, it was a &quot;weapon of the enemy&quot;, one that could benefit Germany but not themselves. In the 1950s, the USA lagged behind the Soviet Union in ballistic missile deployment despite a huge advantage in basic technology. The reason: the USA had an overwhelming bomber force, and a huge investment in it.<br>India has actively researched a nuclear rocket and it is almost a certainty that China has as well. There are others who could pull it off, too. Brazil and Israel need more resources for growing populations, and Israel, at least, is always seeking military advantage. <br>The military advantages of space were made obvious, once again, during the war in Afghanistan. GPS satellites guided bombs, missiles, and ground teams with pinpoint accuracy. Surveillance satellites located areas of interest for close range systems and special forces teams. Ferret satellites eavesdropped on enemy communications. Only the United States has this level of military space capability, because it is the only country that can afford it with chemical rockets. Nuclear rockets could change all this in the blink of an eye.    <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 49<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/12/02 6:37:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Reasons to go nuclear!</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  MONEY!<br><br>Asteroids are goldmines</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br><br>I wonder about supply and demand affecting the long term value of<br>asteroid mining.  If precious minerals are made readily available, and<br>cheap transportation via nuclear rockets is present, wouldn't the<br>value of the material mined plummet because of it's ease of<br>availability?<br><br>Of course, if material mined from asteroids is to be used only in<br>space and not imported to the Earth, then Earth based economics would<br>be unaffected.<br><br>Either way, it would make a good study for an economist.<br><br>Found the following in the Scientific American link posted above:<br><br><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;Recent economic analysis by Jeffrey S. Kargel of the U.S.<br>Geological Survey (co-author of &quot;Global Climatic Change on Mars&quot; in<br>the November 1996 issue of Scientific American) shows that it may be<br>profitable to do this even if the price of precious metals is<br>significantly depressed by a big new supply. Other experts in this<br>field include David Kuck, a consulting geologist in Arizona who has<br>developed concepts for robotic mining, and John Lewis of the<br>University of Arizona, long an advocate of asteroid mining.&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br><br>Guess that answers my question!  Still, it deserves further research<br>in the long term economics of asteroid mining... but don't get me<br>wrong, I'm all for the commercialization of space.<br> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A> at: 1/12/02 6:57:44 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 68<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/12/02 10:28:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fas.org/nuke/hew/Usa/Tests/Rwmohawk2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Reasons to go nuclear!</span><hr size=1> Interestingly I just found this article at our space science news list on the main page. It highlights what we are talking about.<br><br>Asteroid may have slammed mineral wealth into Shark Bay<br><br><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.abc.net.au/news/justin/nat/newsnat-13jan2002-10.htm">www.abc.net.au/news/justin/nat/newsnat-13jan2002-10.htm</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br><br>Geologists say there may be undiscovered mineral wealth in Western Australia, where an asteroid hit the ground near Shark Bay.<br><br>The Woodleigh impact structure was created 360 million years ago when a five-kilometre diameter asteroid slammed into the ground.<br><br>The resultant explosion probably caused life on earth to become extinct, but also changed the make-up of rock in the area.<br><br>Geologist with the Department of Mineral and Petroleum resources Franco Pirajno, says there may be hidden underground wealth at the site.<br><br>&quot;One important feature is the fact that these impact sites constitute areas where you may find mineral deposits, where you may find even petroleum deposits, petroleum reservoirs, because the rocks are shattered,&quot; he said.<br><br>*****************************************************<br><br>A very short article but it backs up what we are saying. Nothing new. We have long known that Asteroid impact sites are rich in mineral wealth. Now why be beggars and scavengers painstakingly searching out what the heavens have thrown down to us. Instead of settling for scraps we could go straight for the source. The outlay would be expensive but as nothing compared to the return. If it was a serious venture I would invest within a heartbeat. Why the mining companies are so quiet on this issue is a mystery to me. <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>Nuclear power is the next logical step for serious space travel. The technology required to colonise the solar system exists now!<a href="http://www.nuclearspace.net/">NUCLEARSPACE.NET</a><img src="http://a676.g.akamai.net/f/676/987/12h/photos.netclubs.com/live/photos/Clubs/t/p/tpeidaeb7nah3e2e0188nkppm4/OrionNow2.gif" border="0"></a> </p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A> at: 1/12/02 10:36:26 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 290<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/7/02 7:14:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fas.org/nuke/hew/Usa/Tests/Rwmohawk2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align